=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span clas=
s=3D"num"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span =
class=3D"den"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> + <link re=
l=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r12144020=
35"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"=
><i>y</i><sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"=
den"><i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> + <link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span=
 class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>z</i>=
<sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den"><i>c=
</i><sup>2</sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> =3D 1</span>: <div class=3D"=
plainlist"><ul><li><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" titl=
e=3D"Sphere">Sphere</a></i>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>b</i> =
=3D <i>c</i> =3D 4</span>, <i>top</i>;</li><li><i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Spheroid" title=3D"Spheroid">Spheroid</a></i>, <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>b</i> =3D 5</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>c</i> =3D 3</span>, <i>bottom left</i>;</li><li><i>Tri-axial</i> ellipsoid=
, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D 4.5</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>b</i> =3D 6</span>; <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =3D 3</span>, <i>bo=
ttom right</i></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure>
<p>An <b>ellipsoid</b> is a surface that can be obtained from a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a> by deform=
ing it by means of directional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sca=
ling_(geometry)" title=3D"Scaling (geometry)">scalings</a>, or more general=
ly, of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_transformation" t=
itle=3D"Affine transformation">affine transformation</a>.
</p><p>An ellipsoid is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadric_s=
urface" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quadric surface">quadric surface</a>=
;=E2=80=8A that is, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(mat=
hematics)" title=3D"Surface (mathematics)">surface</a> that may be defined =
as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_set" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Zero set">zero set</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomial</a> of degree two in th=
ree variables. Among quadric surfaces, an ellipsoid is characterized by eit=
her of the two following properties. Every planar <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Cross_section_(geometry)" title=3D"Cross section (geometry)=
">cross section</a> is either an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
llipse" title=3D"Ellipse">ellipse</a>, or is empty, or is reduced to a sing=
le point (this explains the name, meaning "ellipse-like"). It is <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounded_set" title=3D"Bounded set">bounded</=
a>, which means that it may be enclosed in a sufficiently large sphere.
</p><p>An ellipsoid has three pairwise <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a> <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotational_symmetry" title=3D"Rotational symmet=
ry">axes of symmetry</a> which intersect at a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Central_symmetry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Central symmet=
ry">center of symmetry</a>, called the center of the ellipsoid. The <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_segment" title=3D"Line segment">line=
 segments</a> that are delimited on the axes of symmetry by the ellipsoid a=
re called the <i>principal axes</i>, or simply axes of the ellipsoid. If th=
e three axes have different lengths, the figure is a <b>triaxial ellipsoid<=
/b> (rarely <b>scalene ellipsoid</b>), and the axes are uniquely defined.
</p><p>If two of the axes have the same length, then the ellipsoid is an <i=
>ellipsoid of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_of_revolutio=
n" title=3D"Surface of revolution">revolution</a></i>, also called a <i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spheroid" title=3D"Spheroid">spheroid=
</a></i>. In this case, the ellipsoid is invariant under a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation" title=3D"Rotation">rotation</a> around t=
he third axis, and there are thus infinitely many ways of choosing the two =
perpendicular axes of the same length. In the case of two axes being the sa=
me length:
</p>
<ul><li>If the third axis is shorter, the ellipsoid is a sphere that has be=
en flattened (called an <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oblate_=
spheroid" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Oblate spheroid">oblate spheroid</=
a></i>).</li>
<li>If the third axis is longer, it is a sphere that has been lengthened (c=
alled a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prolate_spheroid" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prolate spheroid">prolate spheroid</a></i>).</li>=
</ul>
<p>If the three axes have the same length, the ellipsoid is a sphere.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Standard_equation">Standard=
 equation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEl=
lipsoid&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Standard =
equation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>The general ellipsoid, also known as triaxial ellipsoid, is a&nbsp;quadr=
atic surface&nbsp;which is defined in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Cartesian_coordinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cart=
esian coordinates</a> as:
