<dl><dt>True curve</dt>
<dd>If one views an ellipsoid from an external point <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> of its focal hyperbola, then i=
t seems to be a sphere, that is its apparent shape is a circle. Equivalentl=
y, the tangents of the ellipsoid containing point <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> are the lines of a circular <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone" title=3D"Cone">cone</a>, whose ax=
is of rotation is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_(geo=
metry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tangent (geometry)">tangent line</a>=
 of the hyperbola at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">V</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipsoid#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipso=
id#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If one allows the center <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> to disappear into infinity, o=
ne gets an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_projection" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orthogonal projection">orthogonal</a> <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_projection" title=3D"Parallel p=
rojection">parallel projection</a> with the corresponding <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asymptote" title=3D"Asymptote">asymptote</a> of the=
 focal hyperbola as its direction. The <i>true curve of shape</i> (tangent =
points) on the ellipsoid is not a circle.<div class=3D"paragraphbreak" styl=
e=3D"margin-top:0.5em"></div> The lower part of the diagram shows on the le=
ft a parallel projection of an ellipsoid (with semi-axes 60, 40, 30) along =
