rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipsoid#cite_note-19"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> In particular:
</p>
<ul><li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diameter" title=3D"Dia=
meter">diameter</a> of the ellipsoid is twice the longest semi-axis, which =
is twice the square-root of the reciprocal of the largest eigenvalue of <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><b>A</b></span>.</li=
>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Width" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Width">width</a> of the ellipsoid is twice the shortest semi-ax=
is, which is twice the square-root of the reciprocal of the smallest eigenv=
alue of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><b>A</b><=
/span>.</li></ul>
<p>An invertible <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_transforma=
tion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear transformation">linear transfor=
mation</a> applied to a sphere produces an ellipsoid, which can be brought =
into the above standard form by a suitable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Rotation" title=3D"Rotation">rotation</a>, a consequence of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_decomposition" title=3D"Polar =
decomposition">polar decomposition</a> (also, see <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_theorem" title=3D"Spectral theorem">spectral theor=
em</a>). If the linear transformation is represented by a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_matrix" title=3D"Symmetric matrix">symmet=
ric 3&nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;3 matrix</a>, then the eigenvectors of the matrix ar=
e orthogonal (due to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_=
theorem" title=3D"Spectral theorem">spectral theorem</a>) and represent the=
 directions of the axes of the ellipsoid; the lengths of the semi-axes are =
computed from the eigenvalues. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Singular_value_decomposition" title=3D"Singular value decomposition">singu=
lar value decomposition</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
lar_decomposition" title=3D"Polar decomposition">polar decomposition</a> ar=
e matrix decompositions closely related to these geometric observations.
</p><p>
