https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haumea" title=3D"Haumea">Haumea</a>, a Jacobi=
-ellipsoid <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_planet" title=3D"=
Dwarf planet">dwarf planet</a>, with its two moons</figcaption></figure>
<p>Ellipsoids and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuboid" title=3D=
"Cuboid">cuboids</a> rotate stably along their major or minor axes, but not=
 along their median axis. This can be seen experimentally by throwing an er=
aser with some spin. In addition, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Moment_of_inertia" title=3D"Moment of inertia">moment of inertia</a> consid=
erations mean that rotation along the major axis is more easily perturbed t=
han rotation along the minor axis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipsoid#cite_note-22"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>One practical effect of this is that scalene astronomical bodies suc=
h as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haumea" title=3D"Haumea">Haum=
ea</a> generally rotate along their minor axes (as does Earth, which is mer=
ely <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oblate_spheroid" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Oblate spheroid">oblate</a>); in addition, because of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tidal_locking" title=3D"Tidal locking=
">tidal locking</a>, moons in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sync=
hronous_orbit" title=3D"Synchronous orbit">synchronous orbit</a> such as <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mimas_(moon)" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Mimas (moon)">Mimas</a> orbit with their major axis aligned radial=
ly to their planet.
</p><p>A spinning body of homogeneous self-gravitating fluid will assume th=
e form of either a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maclaurin_spher=
oid" title=3D"Maclaurin spheroid">Maclaurin spheroid</a> (oblate spheroid) =
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobi_ellipsoid" title=3D"Jaco=
bi ellipsoid">Jacobi ellipsoid</a> (scalene ellipsoid) when in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrostatic_equilibrium" title=3D"Hydrostatic =
equilibrium">hydrostatic equilibrium</a>, and for moderate rates of rotatio=
n.  At faster rotations, non-ellipsoidal <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.o=
rg/wiki/pyriform" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:pyriform">piriform</a> or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oviform" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Oviform">oviform</a> shapes can be expected, but these are not stable.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fluid_dynamics">Fluid dynam=
ics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEllipsoi=
d&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Fluid dynamics=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>The ellipsoid is the most general shape for which it has been possible t=
o calculate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creeping_flow" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Creeping flow">creeping flow</a> of fluid aroun=
d the solid shape. The calculations include the force required to translate=
 through a fluid and to rotate within it. Applications include determining =
the size and shape of large molecules, the sinking rate of small particles,=
 and the swimming abilities of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mic=
roorganisms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Microorganisms">microorganisms<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ellipsoid#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_probability_and_statisti=
cs">In probability and statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DEllipsoid&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=
=3D"Edit section: In probability and statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptical_distribution" ti=
tle=3D"Elliptical distribution">elliptical distributions</a>, which general=
ize the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_normal_distri=
bution" title=3D"Multivariate normal distribution">multivariate normal dist=
ribution</a> and are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finan=
ce" title=3D"Finance">finance</a>, can be defined in terms of their <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Density_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Density function">density functions</a>. When they exist, the densi=
ty functions <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</s=
pan> have the structure:
</p>
