-align: -1.005ex; width:35.067ex; height:3.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle f(=
x)=3Dk\cdot g\left((\mathbf {x} -{\boldsymbol {\mu }}){\boldsymbol {\Sigma =
}}^{-1}(\mathbf {x} -{\boldsymbol {\mu }})^{\mathsf {T}}\right)}"></span></=
dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>=
 is a scale factor, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>x</b></span> is an <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>-dimensional <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Random vector">random row vector</a> with median vector <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>=CE=BC</b></span> (which is also the mean vector if the lat=
ter exists), <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=CE=A3</b></span> is a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_definite_matrix" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Positive definite matrix">positive definite matrix</a> which is =
proportional to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_mat=
rix" title=3D"Covariance matrix">covariance matrix</a> if the latter exists=
, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> is=
 a function mapping from the non-negative reals to the non-negative reals g=
iving a finite area under the curve.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipsoid#cite_note-24"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> The multivariate normal distribution is the special case in which <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>(<i>z</i>) =3D exp(=E2=88=92<link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span=
 class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>z</i>=
</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span>)</span> for quadratic form <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span>.
</p><p>Thus the density function is a scalar-to-scalar transformation of a =
quadric expression. Moreover, the equation for any <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Contour_line" title=3D"Contour line">iso-density surface</=
a> states that the quadric expression equals some constant specific to that=
 value of the density, and the iso-density surface is an ellipsoid.
</p>
